\section{Introduction}

Functional logic programming languages add expressiveness to functional programming
by introducing logical variables, equality constraints among those variables,
and choice to allow multiple alternatives to be explored.  Here is a tiny example:
$$
|def (x ^^ y ^^ z) (x==tup(y,3); x==tup(2,z); y)|
$$
This expression introduces three logical (or existential) variables |x,y,z|,
constrains them with two equalities |(x==tup(y,3)| and |(x==tup(2,z))|, and finally returns |y|.
The only solution to the two equalities is |y==2|, |z==3|, and |x==tup(2,3)|; so the result of the
whole expression is |2|.

Functional logic programming has a long history and a rich literature.
But it is somewhat tricky for programmers to \emph{reason} about
functional logic programs: they must think about logical variables,
narrowing, backtracking, Horn clauses, resolution, and the like.  This
contrasts with functional programming, where one can say ``just apply
rewrite rules, such as \textbeta-reduction, let-inlining, and
case-of-known-constructor.''
% Moreover, these rewrite rules apply even
% in the presence of free variables; {\eg}, under lambdas.
We therefore seek \emph{a precise expression of functional logic programming as
a term-rewriting system}, to give us both a formal semantics (via small-step reductions),
and a powerful set of equivalences that programmers can use to reason about their programs,
and that compilers can use to optimize them.

We make the following contributions in this paper.
First, we describe a new core calculus for functional logic programming,
the Verse calculus or \versecalc{} for short
(\cref{sec:informal}).
As in any functional logic language,
\versecalc{} supports logical variables, equalities, and choice, but it is distinctive in several ways:
\begin{itemize}
\item \versecalc{} natively supports \emph{higher-order functions}, just like the lambda calculus.
  Indeed, \emph{every lambda calculus program is a \versecalc{} program}.
  In contrast, most of the functional logic literature is rooted in a first-order world, and
  addresses higher-order features via an encoding called defunctionalization~\cite[3.3]{hanus:survey}.
\item All functional logic languages have some notion of ``flexible'' {\vs} ``rigid'' variables.
  \versecalc{} offers a new
  way to address these notions, through the operators |oneKW| (\cref{sec:one})
  and |allKW| (\cref{sec:all}).  This enables an elegant economy of concepts: for example,
  there is just one equality (other languages may have a suspending equality and a narrowing equality),
  and conditional expressions are driven by failure rather than booleans (\cref{sec:if}).
\item \emph{Choice and determinism.} Choice is a fundamental feature of all functional logic languages.
  In \versecalc{}, choice is expressed in the syntax of the term (``laid out in space'')
  rather than, as is more typical, handled by non-deterministic rewrites and backtracking (``laid out in time'').
  This makes \versecalc{} completely \emph{deterministic}, unlike most
  functional logic languages which are non-deterministic by design (\cref{sec:deterministic}).
\end{itemize}
As always with a calculus, the idea is that \versecalc{} distills the essence of functional logic programming.
Each construct does just one thing, and \versecalc{} cannot be made smaller without losing key features.
We believe that it is possible to use \versecalc{} as the compilation target for a variety of
functional logic languages such as Curry~\cite{hanus:curry-report}.
We are ourselves working on Verse, a new general purpose programming language, built directly on \versecalc{}; indeed,
our motivation for developing \versecalc{} is practical rather than theoretical.
No single aspect of \versecalc{} is unique, but we believe that their combination
is particularly harmonious and orthogonal.
We discuss the related work in \cref{sec:related}, and design alternatives in \cref{sec:variations}.

Our second contribution is to equip \versecalc{} with a
\emph{small-step term-rewriting semantics} (\cref{sec:rewrite-rules}).
We said that the lambda calculus is a subset of \versecalc{}, so it is natural to give its
semantics using rewrite rules, just like the lambda calculus.  That seems challenging, however, because
logical variables and unification involve sharing and non-local communication. How can that
be expressed in a rewrite system?

Happily, we can build on prior work: exactly the same difficulty arises with call-by-need in the lambda calculus.
For a long time, the only semantics of
call-by-need that was faithful to its sharing semantics (in which thunks are evaluated at most once)
was an operational semantics that sequentially threads a global heap through execution~\cite{launchbury:natural}.
But then Ariola {\etal}, in a seminal paper, showed how to \emph{reify the heap into the term itself},
and thereby build a rewrite system that is completely faithful to lazy evaluation~\cite{ariola:call-by-need}.
Inspired by their idea, we present a new rewrite system for functional logic programs that reifies
logical variables and unification into the term itself,
and replaces non-deterministic search with a (deterministic) tree of successful results.
% Just like rewriting for the lambda calculus, this semantics
% gives programmers a set of equivalences with which
% they can reason equationally about their programs.
For example, the expression above can be rewritten
as follows\footnote{The rule names come from \cref{fig:rules}, to be discussed in \cref{sec:rewrite-rules}; they
  are given here just for reference.}:
$$
\begin{array}{ll@@{\quad}ll}
\multicolumn{4}{l}{|def (x ^^ y ^^ z) (x == tup(y,3); x == tup(2,z); y)|} \\
\movestoR{subst}         & |def (x ^^ y ^^ z) (tup(2,z) == tup(y,3); x == tup(2,z); y)| &
\movestoR{eqn-elim}      & |def (y ^^ z) (tup(2,z) == tup(y,3); y)| \\
\movestoR{u-tup}         & |def (y ^^ z) (2==y; z==3; y)| &
\movestoR{eqn-elim}      & |def y (2==y; y)| \\
\movestoR{hnf-swap}      & |def y (y==2; y)| &
\movestoR{subst}         & |def y (y==2; 2)| \\
\movestoR{eqn-elim}      & |2| \\
\end{array}
$$
%
Rules may be applied anywhere they match, again just like the lambda calculus.
This freedom only makes sense, however, if each term ultimately reduces to a unique value,
regardless of its reduction path,
so we show that \versecalc{} is \emph{confluent}, in \cref{sec:metatheory}.

% There is a rich seam of related work, as we discuss in \cref{sec:related}.

\section{The Verse calculus, informally} \label{sec:informal}

\figureSyntax

We begin by presenting the Verse calculus, \versecalc, informally.  We will describe its
rewrite rules precisely in \cref{sec:rewrite-rules}.
The (abstract) syntax of \versecalc{} is given in \cref{fig:syntax}.
It has a very conventional sub-language that is just the lambda calculus with
some built-in operations and tuples as data constructors:
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Values.}  A value |v| is either a variable |x| or a head-normal form |hnf|.
  In \versecalc{}, a variable counts as a value because in a functional logic language an expression
  may evaluate to an as-yet-unknown logical variable.
  A head-normal form is a conventional value: a built-in constant |k|, an operator |op|, a tuple, or
  a lambda.  Our tiny calculus offers only integer constants |k| and two illustrative integer operators |op|, namely |gt| and |add|.
\item \emph{Expressions} |e| includes values |v|, and applications |apply1N v_1 v_2|; we will
  introduce the other constructs as we go.
For clarity, we often write |apply1 v_1 v_2| rather than |apply1N v_1 v_2| when |v_2| is not a tuple.
\item A term |eq| is either an ordinary expression |e|, or
an \emph{equation} |v==e|; this syntax ensures that equations can only occur to the left of a ``|;|'' (\cref{sec:unify}).
\item \emph{A program}, |p|, is a closed expression from which we extract one result using |oneKW| (see \cref{sec:one}).
%%  \lennart{It's not really supposed top be |OneKW|, but |succeeds|.  But we don't have |succeeds|.}
\end{itemize}
The formal syntax for |e| allows only applications of \emph{values}, |(v_1 v_2)|, but the desugaring
rules in \cref{fig:syntax} show how to desugar more applications |(e_1 e_2)|. This ANF-like
normalization is not fundamental; it simply reduces the number of rewrite rules we need.
The desugaring rules are more suggestive than precise; we aim to be precise about \versecalc{} but
less so about the source language.

Modulo this desugaring, every lambda calculus term is a \versecalc{} term,
and has the same semantics. Just like the lambda calculus, \versecalc{} is untyped;
adding a type system is an excellent goal, but is the subject of another paper.

Expressions also include two other key collections of constructs:
logical variables and unification (\cref{sec:unify}), and choice (\cref{sec:choice}).
The details of choice and unification, and especially their
interaction, are subtle, so this section will do a lot of
arm-waving.  But fear not: \cref{sec:rewrite-rules} will spell out the precise details.
We only have space to describe one incarnation of \versecalc{}; \cref{sec:variations}
explores some possible alternative design choices.

\subsection{Logical variables and equations} \label{sec:unify}

The Verse calculus includes first class \emph{logical variables} and \emph{equations} that constrain their values.
You can bring a fresh logical variable into scope with |defKW|, constrain a value to be equal to
an expression with an equation
|v == e|, and compose expressions in sequence with |eq ; e| (see \cref{fig:syntax}).
As an example, what might be written |llet x e_1 e_2| in a conventional functional language can be written
|def x (x==e_1; e_2)| in \versecalc{}.  The syntax carefully constrains both the form of
equations and where they can appear: an equation |(v==e)| always equates a \emph{value} $v$ to an expression $e$;
and an equation can only appear to the left of a ``|;|'' (see |eq| in \cref{fig:syntax}).
The desugaring rules in \cref{fig:syntax} rewrite a general equation |e_1 == e_2| into this simpler form.

\emph{A program executes by solving its equations}, using the process of unification.
For example,
$$
|def (x ^^ y ^^ z) (x==tup(y,3); x==tup(2,z); y)|
$$
is solved by unifying |x| with |tup(y,3)| and with |tup(2,z)|; that in turn unifies |tup(y,3)| with |tup(2,z)|, which
unifies |y| with |2| and |z| with |3|.  Finally, |2| is returned as the result.
Note carefully that, as in any declarative language,
\emph{logical variables are not mutable}; a logical variable stands for a single, immutable value.
We use ``|defKW|'' to bring a fresh logical variable into scope, because we really
mean ``there exists an |x| such that |xdots|.''
%% Logical variables \emph{are} existential variables.

High-level functional languages usually provide some kind of
pattern matching; in such a language, we might define |first| by
|applyN first (a,b) == a|. Such pattern matching is typically desugared to
more primitive |case| expressions, but in \versecalc{} we do not need |case| expressions:
unification does the job.  For example we can define |first| like this:
$$
|first :== lam p (def (a ^^ b) (p == tup (a,b); a))|
$$
% The lambda unifies its argument (presumably a pair)
%with |tup(a,b)|, where |a,b| are fresh logical
% variables in the body of the lambda; and returns the first of the two, namely |a|.
For convenience, we allow ourselves to write a term like
|applyN first (2,5)|, where we define the library function |first| separately with ``|:==|.'' Formally, you can imagine
each example |e| being wrapped with a binding for |first|, thus |def first (first == ...); e|,
and similarly for other library functions.

This way of desugaring pattern matching means that the input
to |first| is not required to be fully determined when the function is called. For example:
$$
|def (x ^^ y) (x == tup(y,5); 2 == apply1 first x; y)|
$$
Here |apply1 first x| evaluates to |y|, which we then unify with |2|.
Another way to say this is that, as usual in logic programming, we may
constrain the \emph{output} of a function (here |2 == apply1 first x|), and thereby
affect its \emph{input} (here |tup(y,5)|).

Although ``|;|\!'' is called ``sequencing,'' the order of that sequence
is immaterial for equations that do not contain choices (see \Cref{sec:choice} for the latter caveat).
For example,
% foothand not needed, the figure introduces this shorthand
%\footnote{We informally write |3+y| rather than |applyN add (3,y)|, and similarly with other operators.},
consider |(def (x ^^ y) (x == 3+y; y == 7; x))|.  The sub-expression |3+y| is stuck until |y| gets a value.
In \versecalc{}, we can only unify |x| with a \emph{value}---we will see why in \cref{sec:call-time-choice}---and
hence the equation |x==3+y| is stuck.
No matter!  We simply leave it and try some other equation. In this case, we can make progress with |y==7|,
and that in turn unlocks |x == 3+y| because now we know that |y| is |7|, so we can evaluate |3+7| to |10|
and unify |x| with that.  The idea of leaving stuck expressions aside and executing other parts of the
program is called
\emph{residuation}~\cite{hanus:survey}\footnote{Hanus did not invent the terms ``residuation'' and``narrowing,'' but
his survey is an excellent introduction and bibliography.}, and is at the heart of our mantra ``just solve the equations.''

\subsection{Choice} \label{sec:choice} \label{sec:call-time-choice}

In conventional functional programming, an expression evaluates to a single value.
In contrast, a \versecalc{} expression evaluates to zero, one, or many values;
or it can get stuck, which is different from producing zero values.
The expression |fail| yields no values; a value |v| yields one value;
and the choice |e_1 choice e_2| yields all the values
yielded by |e_1| followed by all the values yielded by |e_2|.
Order is maintained and duplicates are not eliminated; we shall see why in \cref{sec:for}.
In short, an expression yields a \emph{sequence} of values, not a bag, and certainly not a set.

The equations we saw in \cref{sec:unify} can fail, if the arguments
are not equal, yielding no results.  Thus |3==3| succeeds,
while |3==4| fails, returning no results.  In general, we use ``fail''
and ``returns no results'' synonymously.

What if the choice was not at the top level of an expression?  For example,
what does |tup (3, (7 choice 5))| mean?
In \versecalc{}, it does \emph{not} mean a pair with some kind of multi-value in its second component.
Indeed, as you can see from \cref{fig:syntax}, this expression is syntactically ill-formed.
We must instead give a name to that choice, and then we can put it in the pair, thus: |def x (x == (7 choice 5); tup (3,x))|.
Now the expression is syntactically legal, but what does it mean?  In \versecalc{}, a variable is never bound to a multi-value.
Instead, |x| is successively bound to |7|, and then to |5|, like this:
$$
|def x (x == (7 choice 5); tup (3,x))| \quad \movesto \quad |(def x (x==7; tup (3,x))) choice (def x (x==5; tup (3,x))))|
$$
We duplicate the context surrounding the choice, and ``float the choice outwards.''
The same thing happens when there are multiple choices.  For example:
$$
|def (x ^^ y) (x == (7 choice 22); y == (31 choice 5); tup (x,y))|
\quad
\text{yields the sequence |tup (7,31), tup(7,5), tup(22,31), tup(22,5)|}
$$
Notice that the order of the two equations now \emph{is} significant:
$$
|def (x ^^ y) y == (31 choice 5); x == (7 choice 22); tup (x,y)|
\quad
\text{yields the sequence |tup (7,31), tup(22,31), tup(7,5), tup(22,5)|}
$$
Readers familiar with list comprehensions in Haskell and other
languages will recognize this nested-loop pattern, but here it
emerges naturally from choice as a deeply built-in primitive,
rather than being a special construct for lists.

Just as we never bind a variable to a multi-value, we never bind it to |fail| either; rather
we iterate over zero values, and that iteration of course returns zero
values.  So:
$$
|def x (x == fail; 33)| \quad \movesto \quad |fail|
$$

\subsection{Mixing choice and equations} \label{sec:mixing}

In the last section, we discussed what happens if there is a choice in the right-hand side (RHS) of
an equation. What if we have equations under choice?  For example:
$$
|def x ((x==3; x+1) choice (x==4; x*2))|
$$
Intuitively, ``either unify |x| with |3| and yield |x+1|, or unify |x| with |4| and yield |x*2|''.
But there is a problem: so far we have said only ``a program executes by solving its equations'' (\cref{sec:unify}).
Here, we can see two equations, |(x==3)| and |(x==4)|, which are mutually contradictory,
so clearly we need to refine our notion of ``solving.''
The answer is pretty clear: in a branch of a choice, solve the equations in that branch
to get the value for some logical variables, \emph{and propagate those values to occurrences in
  that branch (only)}. Occurrences of that variable outside the choice are unaffected.  We call
this \emph{local propagation}.
This local-propagation rule would allow us to reason thus:
$$
|def x ((x==3; x+1) choice (x==4; x*2))| \movesto  |def x ((x==3; 4) choice (x==4; 8))|
$$
Are we stuck now?  No, we can float the choice out as
before\footnote{Indeed, we could have done so first, had we wished.},
$$
|def x ((x==3; 4) choice (x==4; 8))| \movesto |(def x (x==3; 4)) choice (def x (x==4; 8))|
$$
and now it is apparent that the sole occurrence of |x| in each |defKW| is the equation
|(x==3)|, or |(x==4)| respectively; so we can drop the |defKW| and the equation, yielding |(4 choice 8)|.
% To take a celebrated example, suppose
% |square = lam x (x*x)|.  What does |apply1 square (3 choice 4)| mean? If we make the choice \emph{before}
% the call, the call will yield |9 choice 16|.  But if we a more call-by-name semantics, we might imagine
% it yields |(3 choice 4) * (3 choice 4)| which in turn yields |(9 choice 12 choice 12 choice 16)|.
% All functional-logic languages, including

\subsection{Pattern matching and narrowing}

We remarked in \cref{sec:unify} that we can desugar the pattern matching of a high-level
language into equations. But what about multi-equation pattern matching, such as this definition in Haskell:
\begin{code}
  append []       ysl == ysl
  append (x:xsl)  ysl == x : append xsl ysl
\end{code}
If pattern matching on the first equation fails, we want to fall through to the second.
Fortunately, choice allows us to express this idea directly, where
we use the empty tuple |emptytup| to represent the empty list and pairs to represent cons cells
(see \cref{fig:syntax} to desugar the pattern matching lambda):
$$
|append :== lam (tup (xsl,ysl))
  (((xsl == emptytup; ysl) choice
   (def (x ^^ xr) (xsl == tup (x,xr); tup (x, applyN append (xr, ysl))))))|
$$
If |xsl| is |emptytup|, the left-hand choice succeeds, returning |ysl|; and the right-hand choice
fails (by attempting to unify |emptytup| with |tup(x,xr)|).
If |xsl| is of the form |tup (x,xr)|,
the right-hand choice succeeds, and we make a recursive call to |append|.
Finally, if |xsl| is built with head-normal forms other than the empty tuple and pairs, both choices fail, and |append| returns no
results at all.

This approach to pattern matching is akin to \emph{narrowing}~\cite{hanus:survey}.
Suppose |single == tup (1, emptytup)|, a singleton list whose only element is 1.
Consider the call |def zsl (applyN append ( zsl, single) == single; zsl)|.
The call to |append| expands into a choice:
$$
  |(zsl == emptytup; single)| \quad |choice| \quad
  |(def (x ^^ xr) (zsl == tup (x,xr); tup(x, applyN append (xr, single))))|
$$
which amounts to exploring the possibility that |zsl| is headed by |emptytup| or a pair---the
essence of narrowing.  It should not take long to reassure yourself that the program
evaluates to |emptytup|, effectively running |append| backwards in the classic logic-programming manner.

This example also illustrates that \versecalc{} allows an equation (for |append|)
that is recursive. As in any functional language with recursive bindings, you can
go into an infinite loop if you keep fruitlessly inlining the function in its own right-hand side.
It is the business of an \emph{evaluation strategy} to do only rewrites that make
progress toward a solution (\cref{sec:eval-strategy}).

\subsection{Conditionals and \texorpdfstring{|oneKW|}{``one''}} \label{sec:rigid} \label{sec:one} \label{sec:if}

Every source language will provide a conditional, such as |if (x==0) then
e_2 else e_3|.  But what is the equality operator in |(x==0)|?  One
possibility, adopted by Curry, is this: there is one ``='' for
equations (as in \cref{sec:unify}), and another, say ``=='', for
testing equality (returning a boolean with constructors |True| and |False|).  \versecalc{} takes a
different, more minimalist position, following Icon's lead, see \cref{sec:icon}.
In \versecalc{}, \emph{there is just one equality operator}, written ``='' just as in
\cref{sec:unify}. The expression |if (x==0) then e_2 else e_3| tries to unify |x| with |0|.  If that succeeds (yields one or more values),
the |if| returns |e_2|; otherwise it returns |e_3|.  There are no data constructors |True| and |False|; instead
failure (returning zero values) plays the role of falsity.

But something is terribly wrong here.  Consider |def (x ^^ y) (y == (if (x==0) then 3 else 4); x==7)|.  Presumably this is meant
to set |x| to |7|, test whether it is equal to |0| (it is not), and unify |y| with 4.
But what is to stop us instead unifying |x| with |0| (via |(x==0)|), unifying |y| with |3|, and then
failing when we try to unify |x| with |7|?  Not only is that not what we intended, but it also looks very
non-deterministic: the result is affected by the order in which we did unifications.

To address this, we give |if| a special property: in the expression |if e_1 then e_2 else e_3|, equations inside |e_1| (the condition of the |if|)
can only unify variables bound inside |e_1|; variables bound outside |e_1| are called ``rigid.''  So in our example, the |x| in |(x==0)| is
rigid and cannot be unified.  Instead, the |if| is stuck, and we move on to unify |x==7|.  That unblocks
the |if| and all is well.
% This special property is precisely the local propagation rule that we sketched for
% choice (\cref{sec:mixing}).

In fact, \versecalc{} desugars the three-part |if| into something simpler, the unary construct |one(e)|.
Its specification is this:
if |e| fails, |one(e)| fails; otherwise |one(e)| returns the first of the values yielded by |e|.
Now, |if e_1 then e_2 else e_3| can (nearly) be re-expressed like this:
$$
|one( (e_1; e_2) choice e_3 )|
$$
This isn't right yet, but the idea is this: if |e_1| fails, the first branch of the choice fails, so we get |e_3|; if |e_1| succeeds, we
get |e_2|, and the outer |oneKW| will select it from the choice.
But what if |e_2| or |e_3| \emph{themselves} fail or return multiple results?  Here is a better translation,
given in \cref{fig:syntax}\footnote{The translation in the figure also allow variables bound in the condition to scope over the |then| branch.}, which wraps the |then| and |else| branches
in a thunk\footnote{Using thunks for the branches of a conditional is another very old idea;
for example, see \cite[p.\ 54]{steele:rabbit}.}:
$$
|apply0 (one( (e_1; (thunk (e_2))) choice (thunk (e_3))))|
$$
The argument of |oneKW| reduces to either |(thunk e_2) `choice` (thunk e_3)| or |(thunk e_3)| depending on whether |e_1| succeeds or fails,
respectively; |oneKW| then picks the first value, that is |thunk e_2| if |e_1| succeeded, or |thunk e_3| if |e_1| failed, and
applies it to |tup ()|.
As a bonus, provided we do no evaluation under a lambda, then |e_2| and |e_3| will
remain unevaluated until the choice is made, just as we expect from a conditional.

We use the same local-propagation rule for |oneKW| that we do for choice (\cref{sec:mixing}).
This, together with the desugaring for |if| into |oneKW|, gives the ``special property'' of |if| described above.

\subsection{Tuples and \texorpdfstring{|allKW|}{``all''}} \label{sec:tuple}

The main data structure in \versecalc{} is the \emph{tuple}.
A tuple is a finite sequence of values, |tup (v_1,dots,v_n)|, where $n\geq 0$.
A tuple can be used like a function: indexing is simply function application
with the argument being integers from 0 and up.  Indexing out of range is |fail|, as is indexing with
a non-integer value.
For example, |t :== tup (10,27,32); apply1 t 1| reduces to |27| and |apply1 t 3| reduces to |fail|.

What if we apply a tuple to a choice, thus |apply1 (tup (10,27,32))(1 `choice` 0 `choice` 1)|?  First we must
desugar the application to the form |(apply1N v_1 v_2)|, because that is all \versecalc{} permits (\cref{fig:syntax}),
giving |x:==(1 `choice` 0 `choice` 1); apply1(tup (10,27,32)) x|, which readily reduces to |(27 `choice` 10 `choice` 27)|.

Tuples can be constructed by collecting all the results from a multi-valued expression, using the |allKW| construct:
if |e| reduces to |(v_1 `choice` xdots `choice` v_n)|, where $n \geq 2$, then |all e| reduces to
the tuple |tup (v_1, dots, v_n)|; |all v| produces the singleton tuple |tup v|; and |all fail| produces the empty tuple |emptytup|.
Note that |choice| is associative, which means that we
can think of a sequence or tree of binary choices as really being a single
$n$-way choice.
\label{sec:all}

You might think that tuple indexing would be stuck until we know the index,
but in \versecalc{}, the application of a tuple to a value rewrites to a choice of all the possible
values of the index.
For example,
|t :== tup (10,27,32); def i (apply1 t i)|
looks stuck because we have no value for |i|, but actually rewrites to:
$$
|def i ((i==0; 10) choice (i==1; 27) choice (i==2; 32)|
$$
which (as we will see in \cref{sec:rewrite-rules}) simplifies
to just |(10 `choice` 27 `choice` 32)|.
So |allKW| allows a choice to be reified into a tuple; and |(def i (apply1 t i))| allows a
tuple to be turned back into a choice.
The idea of rewriting a call of a function with a finite domain into a finite choice
is called ``narrowing'' in the literature.

Do we even need |oneKW| as a primitive construct, given that we have
|allKW|? Can we not use |apply1 (all e) 0| instead of |one e|? Indeed,
they behave the same if |e| fully reduces to finitely many choices of
values. But |allKW| really requires \emph{every} arm of the choice tree to resolve to a value
before proceeding, while |oneKW| only needs the
\emph{first} choice to be a value. So, supposing that |loop| is a non-terminating function,
|one (1 `choice` apply0 loop)| can reduce to 1, while
|apply1 (all (1 `choice` apply0 loop)) 0| loops.

\subsection{Programming in Verse}  \label{sec:verse}

\versecalc{} is a fairly small language, but it is quite expressive.
For example, we can define the typical list functions one would expect from functional programming
by using the duality between tuples and choices, as seen in \cref{fig:list-functions}.
A tuple can be turned into choices by indexing with a logical variable |i|.
Conversely, choices can be turned into a tuple using |allKW|.
The choice operator, |choice|, serves as both |cons| and |append| for choices;
the corresponding operations for tuples are defined in \cref{fig:list-functions}.
Partial functions, \eg, |head|, will |fail| when the argument is outside of the domain.

