Pattern matching for function definitions is simply done by unification of ordinary expressions;
see the desugaring of pattern-matching lambda in \cref{fig:syntax}.
This in turn means that we can use ordinary abstraction mechanisms for patterns.
For example, here is a function, |fcn|, that could be called as follows: |applyN fcn (88,1,99,2)|.
$$
\begin{array}{l}
|apply1 fcn t :== def (x ^^ y) (t == tup(x,1,y,2); x+y)|
\end{array}
$$
If we want to give a name to the pattern, it is simple to do so:
$$
|applyN pat (v,w) :== tup(v,1,w,2);| \quad \quad
|apply1 fcn t :== def (x ^^ y) (t == applyN pat (x,y); x+y)|
$$
Patterns are truly first class, going well beyond what can be done with, say, pattern synonyms
in Haskell.  For example, |pat| could be \emph{computed}, like this:
$$
|applyN pat (a,v,w) :== if a==0 then tup (v,1,w,2) else tup (1,1,w,v)|
$$
so that the pattern depends on the value of |a|.

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{|for|}{``for''} loops} \label{sec:for}

The expression |fordo e_1 e_2| will evaluate |e_2| for each of the choices in |e_1|,
rather like a list comprehension in languages like Haskell or Python.
% The |e_1| is called the \emph{domain} of the loop.
The scoping is peculiar\footnote{But similar to C++, Fortress, and Swift, and explained by
  the subsequent desugaring into |allKW|.}
in that variables bound in |e_1| also scope over |e_2|.
So, for example, |fordo(x :== 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5) (x+1)| will reduce to the tuple |tup (3,4,6)|.
% This example can, with the |:==| shorthand, be written |for^(x :== 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5) do (x+1)|.

Like list comprehension, |for| supports filtering; in \versecalc{}, this falls out naturally by just using
a possibly failing expression in |e_1|.
So, |fordo(x :== 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5; x > 2) (x+1)| reduces to |tup (4,6)|.
Nested iteration in a |for| works as expected and requires nothing special.
So, |fordo(def (x^^y) (x==10 `choice` 20; y == 1 `choice` 2 `choice` 3)) (x+y)| reduces to |tup (11, 12, 13, 21, 22, 23)|.

Just as |if| is defined in terms of the primitive |oneKW| (\cref{sec:if}), we can define |for|
in terms of the primitive |allKW|.
Again, we have to be careful when |e_2| itself fails or produces multiple results;
simply writing |all (e_1;e_2)| would give the wrong semantics. So we put |e_2| under a lambda, and
apply each element of the tuple to |emptytup| afterwards, using a |map| function (as defined in \cref{fig:list-functions}):
\[
|fordo(def (x_1^^xdots^^x_n) e_1) e_2| \quad \text{means} \quad
|v :== all (def (x_1^^xdots^^x_n) e_1; thunk e_2); applyN map (lam z (apply0 z), v))|
\]
for a fresh variable |v|.
Note how this achieves that peculiar scoping rule: the initial variables in |def (x_1^^xdots^^x_n) e_1| are in scope in |e_2|.
Moreover, any effects (like being multi-valued) in |e_2| will not affect the choices defined by |e_1| since they are inside that lambda.
So, for example, |fordo(x:==10 `choice` 20) (x `choice` x+1)| will reduce to
|tup (10, 20) `choice` tup (10, 21) `choice` tup (11, 20) `choice` tup (11, 21)|.
At this point, it is crucial that the desugaring of |for| uses |map|, not |flatMap|.

Given that tuple indexing expands into choices, we can iterate over tuple indices and elements using |for|.
For example, |fordo(def (i ^^ x) (x == apply1 t i)) (x+i)| produces a tuple with the elements of |t|, increased by their index in |t|.  Notice the absence of the
fencepost-error-prone iteration of |i| over |(0..size(t)-1)|, common in most languages.


