\subsection{Functions and function application rules} \label{sec:beta}

Looking at \cref{fig:rules}, rule \rulename{app-add}
should be familiar: it simply rewrites an application of |add| to integer
constants.  For example $|applyN add (3,4)| \movesto |7|$.  Rules \rulename{app-gt} and
\rulename{app-gt-fail} are more interesting: |applyN gt (k_1,k_2)| fails if $k_1 \leq k_2$ (rather than returning |False| as is more conventional), and returns |k_1| otherwise (rather than returning |True|).
An amusing consequence is that |(10 > x > 0)| succeeds
iff |x| is between |10| and |0| (comparison is right-associative).

% Rule \rulename{p-map} implements a map operation over tuples: It applies the function |f| to each value
% in turn, and collects the results into a tuple. If the function applications produce a choice
% of values, this will, as it should, produce a choice of tuples:
% \[
% |applyN map ((lam x (x choice  x+1)), (10,20))| \movesto^\ast |(10,20) choice (10,21) choice (11,20) choice (11,21)|
% \]
\textbeta-reduction is performed quite conventionally by \rulename{app-beta}; the
only unusual feature is that on the RHS of the rule, we use an |defKW| to bind |x|,
together with |(x==v)| to equate |x| to the argument.
The rule may appear to use call-by-value, because the argument is a value |v|,
but remember that values include variables, which may be bound to an
as-yet-unevaluated expression.  For example:
$$
|def y (y == 3+4; apply1 (lam x (x+1)) y)|
\; \movesto \;
|def y (y == 3+4; def x (x==y; x+1))|
$$
Finally, the side condition $x \not\in \freevars{v}$ in \rulename{app-beta}
ensures that the $|defKW| |x|$
% hacky typesetting to ge the \exists right next to the x.
does not capture any variables free in |v|.  If |x| appears free in |v|,
\textalpha-conversion may be used on |lam x e| to rename |x| to $y \not\in \freevars{v}$.

In \versecalc{}, tuples behave like (finite) functions in which application is
indexing.  Rule \rulename{app-tup} describes how tuple application works on non-empty
tuples, while \rulename{app-tup-0} deals with empty tuples.
Notice that \rulename{app-tup} does not require the argument to be evaluated to an integer $k$; instead
the rule works by narrowing.  So the expression |def x (apply1 (tup(2,3,2,7,9)) x == 2; x)|
does not suspend awaiting a value for |x|; instead it explores all the
alternatives, returning |(0 choice 2)|.  This is a free design decision:
a suspending semantics would be equally easy to express.

\subsection{Unification rules} \label{sec:unification-rules}

Next we study unification, again in \cref{fig:rules}.
Rules \rulename{u-lit} and \rulename{u-tup}
are the standard rules for unification, going back nearly 60 years \cite{robinson:unification}.
% Note that
% when unification succeeds it yields the common value; hence |s == s| rewrites
% to |s|\footnote{An alternative choice would
% for unification to yield |emptytup| on success.  It does not make much difference
% either way.}.
Rule \rulename{u-fail} makes unification fail on two different head-normal forms (see
\cref{fig:syntax} for the syntax of |hnf|).
Note in particular that unification fails if you attempt to unify a
lambda with any other value, including itself (see \cref{sec:unifying-lambda}).

The standard ``occurs check'' is rule \rulename{u-occurs}, which makes use of a
\emph{context} |V|, whose syntax is given in \cref{fig:contexts}
\cite{felleisen:contexts1,felleisen:contexts2}.
In general, a context is a syntax tree containing a single hole, written |hole|.
The notation |V^[v]| is the term obtained by filling the hole
in |V| with |v|.  For example, \rulename{u-occurs} reduces |x == tup(1,x,3)| to |fail|
using the context |V| = |tup( 1, hole , 3)|.


% Failure, written |fail|, propagates upwards, as \rulename{fail-def} and \rulename{fail} show.
% The latter rule makes use of an \emph{execution context}, |X|,
% whose syntax is given in \cref{fig:contexts}.
% In general, a ``context'' is a syntactic construct (in this case an expression)
% containing a single hole, written |hole| \cite{felleisen:contexts1,felleisen:contexts2}.
% The notation |X^[e]| is the expression obtained by filling the hole
% in |X| with |e|.
% For example |(y == tup (hole, 4))| is a possible execution context, |X|; filling its hole with 99
% gives the expression $|X^[99]| \equiv |(y == tup (99,4))|$.
% So \rulename{fail} says that if |fail| occurs in an |X|-context, thus |X^[fail]|, we can rewrite
% it to |fail|, discarding |X| altogether. For example |(x==y; fail; 3)| rewrites to |fail|.

% \subsection{Unification: the \rulename{subst} rule}

The key innovation in \versecalc{} is the way bindings (that is, just ordinary equalities)
of logical variables are propagated.
The key rule is:
$$
\begin{array}{rrcll}
  \rulename{subst} & |X^[x==v;e]| & \movesto & |(subst X x v)^[x==v; subst e x v]| \hspace*{-0.3em}
    & \text{if $|x| \in \freevars{|X,e|}$, $|x| \notin \freevars{v}$} \\
  &&&& \text{and $|v| = |y| \implies |x| \prec |y|$} \\
\end{array}
$$
The rule says that if we have an equation |(x==v)|,
we can replace the occurrences of |x| by |v| in its surrounding context |X|.
This rule makes use of new context |X| (see \cref{fig:contexts}), and
uses the notation |subst X x v| to mean ``substitute |v| for |x| in |X|'' and
similarly |subst e x v|.
There are several things to notice:
\begin{itemize}
\item \rulename{subst} fires only when the right-hand side of the equation
  is a \emph{value} |v|, so that the substitution does not risk
  duplicating either work or choices. This
restriction is precisely the same as the \rulename{let-v} rule of \citet{ariola:call-by-need}
and, by not duplicating choices, it neatly implements so-called \emph{call-time choice}~\cite{hanus:survey}.
We do not need a heap, or thunks, or updates; the equalities of the program elegantly
suffice to express the necessary sharing.
\item \rulename{subst} replaces all occurrences of |x| in |X| and |e|, but
  \emph{it leaves the original |(x==v)| undisturbed}, because |X| might not be
  big enough to encompass all occurrences of |x|.
  For example, we can rewrite |(y==x+1; (x==3; z==x+3))| to |(y==x+1; (x==3; z==3+3))|, using
  |X == (hole; z==x+3)|, but that leaves an occurrence of |x| in |(y==x+1)|.
  When there are no remaining occurrences of |x| we may eliminate
  the binding: see \cref{sec:gc}.
\item The side condition $x \not\in \freevars{v}$ in \rulename{subst} prevents infinite substitution,
  while $x \in \freevars{X,e}$ ensures that there is at least one occurrence to substitute.
  The other side condition will be explained next, when we discuss \rulename{var-swap}.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Swapping and binding order} \label{sec:swapping}

Rules \rulename{hnf-swap} helps \rulename{subst} to fire by putting the variable on the left.
Rule \rulename{var-swap} is trickier.  Consider this example where |a| and |b| are
bound further out, perhaps by lambdas.  It can rewrite in two different ways:
$$
\begin{array}{l@@{\,}l@@{\hspace{1cm}}l@@{\,}l}
  \multicolumn{4}{c}{|def x (x == tup a ; x == tup b; x)|} \\
  \movestoR{subst} & |def x (x == tup a ; tup a == tup b; tup a)| &
     \movesto & |def x (tup b == tup a ; x == tup b; tup b)| \\
  \movestoR{u-tup, eqn-elim} & |a == b; tup a| &
     \movesto & |b == a; tup b| \\
  \movestoR{subst} & |a == b; tup b| &
      \movesto & |b == a; tup a| \\

\end{array}
$$
Each column is a reduction sequence starting from the same common term at the top;
the two sequences differ when it comes to which equation for |x| is chosen for \rulename{subst}
in the first step. As you can see, they conclude with two terms that are ``obviously''
the same, but which are syntactically different.  Rule \rulename{var-swap} allows
them to be brought together, so that the unification rules are confluent.
Rule \rulename{seq-swap} is needed for a similar reason. Consider
this example:
% where |a,b,c| are bound in that order; \ie, $|c| \prec |b| \prec |a|$:
$$
\begin{array}{l@@{\,}l@@{\hspace{1cm}}l@@{\,}l}
  \multicolumn{4}{c}{|c==a; c==b; c|} \\
  \movestoR{subst} & |c==a; a==b; a| &
     \movestoR{subst} & |b==a; c==b; b| \\

  \movestoR{var-swap} & |c==a; b==a; a| &
     \movestoR{subst}   & |b==a; c==a; a| \\
\end{array}
$$
Again, the concluding terms of the two columns are ``obviously'' the same,
because they differ only in the order of the equations |(b==a)| and |(c==a)|;
\rulename{seq-swap} allows them to be brought together, and makes explicit
our intuition that order of equations |(x=v)| does not matter.
% Both \rulename{var-swap} and \rulename{seq-swap} are needed only for \emph{confluence},
% not for \emph{progress}. \simon{I think this is true of both, isn't it?}
% \lennart{Without \rulename{var-swap} I think we need another \rulename{eqn-elim} rule for the |y==x| case.}
% \lennart{We also don't need \rulename{exi-swap} if we a stronger \rulename{eqn-elim}.}

Next we study the mysterious $x \prec y$ side condition in \rulename{var-swap},
and similar ones in \rulename{subst} and \rulename{seq-swap}.
In the overall proof of confluence, it turns out to
be very helpful if the unification rules
are \emph{terminating} (see \cref{sec:design-confluence}).
To achieve this, \rulename{var-swap} fires on |y==x| \emph{only if
|x| is bound inside |y|}, written $|x| \prec |y|$, so that the innermost-bound variable
ends up on the left.
Similarly, the side condition on \rulename{seq-swap} prevents it firing infinitely;
and the side condition $(|v| = |y| \implies |x| \prec |y|)$ on \rulename{subst}
prevents the rule from firing until \rulename{var-swap} has done its work.

Other rules, notably \rulename{exi-swap}, may change this binding order
and thereby re-enable \rulename{var-swap} or \rulename{seq-swap},
but the unification rules \emph{considered in isolation} are terminating and confluent,
and that is what we need for the proof.

\subsection{Local substitution} \label{sec:local-subst}

Consider this (extremely) tricky term:
|def x (x = if (x==0; x>1) then 33 else 55)|.
What should this do? At first you might think it was stuck---how can we simplify the |if|
when its condition mentions |x| which is not yet defined?  But in fact, rule \rulename{subst} allows
us to substitute \emph{locally} in any X-context surrounding the equation |(x==0)|
thusly:\footnote{
  Here and elsewhere we rewrite terms that have not
  been fully desugared, but that is just an expository aid;
  formally, the rules apply only to programs in the language of \cref{fig:syntax}.}
$$
\begin{array}{l@@{\;}l}
\multicolumn{2}{l}{|def x (x = if (x==0; x>1) then 33 else 55; x)|} \\
\movestoR{subst}                & |def x (x = if (x==0; 0>1) then 33 else 55; x)| \\
\movestoR{app-gt-fail,fail-elim}     & |def x (x = if fail then 33 else 55; x)| \\
\multicolumn{2}{l}{\movestoC{\text{simplify |if|}} \; |def x (x = 55; x)| \quad
\movestoR{subst} \; |def x (x = 55; 55)| \quad
\movestoR{exi-elim}  \; |55|}
\end{array}
$$
Minor variants of the same example get stuck instead of reducing. For example, if you replace
the |(x==0)| with |(x==100)| then rewriting gets stuck, as the reader may verify; and yet there
is a solution to the equations, namely |x==55|.
And if you replace |(x==0)| with |(x==55)|, then rewriting again
gets stuck, and reasonably so, since in this case there are \emph{no} valid solutions to the equations.
Perhaps this is not surprising: we cannot reasonably expect the program to solve arbitrary equations.
For example, |def x (x*x = x)| has two solutions but discovering that involves solving a quadratic equation.

