\subsection{Elimination and normalization rules} \label{sec:gc} \label{sec:normalization}

% Indeed, |e| can mention |x| too: consider |(x == ((y==x+1); 3); y)|. Using
% \rulename{eqn-float} gives us |(y==x+1; x==3; y)|; to make further progress we must
% move the |x==3| to the left, using \rulename{seq-assoc-swap2}, giving |(x==3; y==x+1; y)|.
% Now we can substitute for |x|, and then for |y|.

Four \emph{elimination} rules allow dead code to be dropped (\cref{fig:rules}):
\rulename{val-elim} discards a value to the left of a semicolon; \rulename{exi-elim} discards
a dead existential; \rulename{eqn-elim} discards an existential $|defKW| |x|$ whose only
occurrence is an equation |x=v|; and \rulename{fail-elim} discards the context surrounding a |fail|.
Note that none of these rules, except \rulename{fail-elim}, discard an unevaluated expression,
because that expression might fail and we don't want to ``lose'' that failure (c.f. \cref{sec:lenient}).
The exception is \rulename{fail-elim}, which propagates failure.

Four \emph{normalization} rules help to put the expression in a form that
allows other rules to fire (\cref{fig:rules}):  \rulename{exi-float} allows an existential to float outwards;
\rulename{seq-assoc} makes semicolon right-associated; \rulename{eqn-float} moves work out
of the right-hand side of an equation |v==e|.
For example, we cannot use \rulename{subst} to substitute for |x| in |(x == (e; 3); x+2)|,
because the RHS of the |x|-equation is not a value; but we can instead apply \rulename{eqn-float}
to get |(e; x==3); x+2|, and then \rulename{seq-assoc} to get |e; x==3; x+2|; and now we \emph{can}
apply \rulename{subst}.

Rule \rulename{exi-swap} allows you to move an existential inward so that a dead equation can be eliminated
by \rulename{eqn-elim}.
Rule \rulename{exi-swap} is unusual because it can be infinitely applied;
avoiding that eventuality is easily achieved by tweaking the evaluation strategy (\cref{sec:eval-strategy}).

Note that all these swapping and normalization rules \emph{preserve the left-to-right sequencing of expressions},
which matters because choices are made left to right as we saw in \cref{sec:mixing}.
Moreover, the rules do not float equalities or existentials out of choices:
that restriction is the key to localizing unification (\cref{sec:mixing}), and
the flexible/rigid distinction of
\cref{sec:rigid}. For example, consider the expression
|(y == ((x==3; x*2) choice (x==4)); tup (x+1,y))|.
We must not float the binding |(x==3)| to the expression |(x+1)|,
because the latter is outside the choice, and a different branch of the choice binds |x| to |4|.

% If the equality |(x==v)| turns out to be the sole remaining occurrence of |x| in
% the body of an |defKW|, then rule \rulename{def-eliml} can drop both the |defKW|
% and the unification equation, and similarly \rulename{def-elimr} if the equation is ordered the other way.
%
% A number of rules shuffle expressions about in order to make
% the main unification rules apply.
% The rule \rulename{swap} swaps the arguments to unification to put the variable on the left.
% Rule \rulename{def-float} moves an |defKW| ``out of the way.'' For example,
% the expression |(y == (def x (tup (x,2))); dots)| does not bind |y| to a value, but if we float the |defKW| out
% we get |def x (y==tup(x,2); dots)|, and now we may be able to make progress by substituting for |y|.
%
% Similarly, rules \rulename{unify-seql} and \rulename{unify-seqr} move sequencing out of unification,
% again to make it more likely to get the form |(x==v)|.  Notice that |e_1|, |e_2| and |e_3| stay in the
