\subsection{Rules for choice} \label{sec:choice-rules}

The rules for choice are given in \cref{fig:rules}:
\begin{itemize}
\item Rules \rulename{one-fail}, \rulename{one-value}, and \rulename{one-choice} describe
  the semantics of |oneKW|, as in \cref{sec:one}.
\item Similarly, \rulename{all-fail}, \rulename{all-value}, and \rulename{all-choice} describe
  the semantics of |allKW| (\cref{sec:all}).
\item Rules \rulename{choose-r} and \rulename{choose-l} eliminate |fail|, which behaves as
  an identity for choice.
\item Rule \rulename{choose-assoc} associates choice to the right, so that \rulename{one-choice}/\rulename{all-choice}
  can fire.  (The dots on the left of \rulename{all-choice} should be read as
  a string of right-associated choices.)
\end{itemize}
The most interesting rule is \rulename{choose}, which, just as described in \cref{sec:choice},
``floats the choice outwards,'' duplicating the surrounding context.
But what ``surrounding context'' precisely? We use two new contexts, |SX| and |CX|, both
defined in \cref{fig:syntax}. A \emph{choice context} |CX| is like an
execution context |X|, \emph{but with no possible
  choices to the left of the hole}:
$$
CX ::= \hole \vb |v == CX| \vb |CX ; e| \vb |ce; CX| \vb |def x CX|
$$
Here, |ce| is a guaranteed-choice-free expression (syntax in \cref{fig:choice-free-syntax}).
This syntactic condition is necessarily conservative; for example, a call |apply1 f x|
is considered not guaranteed-choice-free because it depends on what function |f| does.
We must guarantee not to have choices to the left so that we preserve order---see \cref{sec:mixing}.

The context |SX| (\cref{fig:contexts}) in \rulename{choose} ensures that |CX| is as large as possible.
This is a very subtle point:
without this restriction we lose confluence.  To see this, consider\footnote{Remember, |if| is syntactic sugar for
  a use of |oneKW|, see \cref{sec:one}, but using |if| makes the example easier to understand.}:
$$
\begin{array}{l@@{\;}l}
                                 & |def x ((if (x>0) then 55 else (44 `choice` 2)); x==1; (77 choice 99))|\\
 \movestoR{subst}                & |def x ((if (1>0) then 55 else (44 `choice` 2)); x==1; (77 choice 99))|\\
 \movestoC{\text{simplify |if|}} & |def x (55; x==1; (77 choice 99))|\\
 \movestoR{val-elim, eqn-elim}   & |77 choice 99|\\
\end{array}
$$
But suppose instead we floated the choice out, \emph{partway}, like this:
$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\multicolumn{2}{l}{|def x ((if (x>0) then 55 else (44 `choice` 2)); x==1; (77 choice 99))|}\\
\quad \movestoC{\text{Bogus \rulename{choose}}} & |def x ((if (x>0) then 55 else (44 `choice` 2));
                            ((x==1; 77) choice (x==1; 99)))|\\
\end{array}
$$
Now the |(x==1)| is inside the choice branches, so we cannot use \rulename{subst} to
substitute for |x| in the condition of the |if|.
Nor can we use \rulename{choose} again to float the choice further out
because the |if| is not guaranteed choice-free (in this case the |else| branch has a choice).
So, alas, we are stuck!
Our not-entirely-satisfying solution is to force \rulename{choose} to float the choice all the way
to the top.  The |SX| context (\cref{fig:contexts}) formalizes what we mean by ``the top'':
rule \rulename{choose} can float a choice outward only when it becomes part of
the choice tree (context |SC|) immediately under a |oneKW| or |allKW| construct (context |SX|).

Rule \rulename{choose} moves choices around; only \rulename{one-choice} and \rulename{all-choice}
\emph{decompose} choices.
So choice behaves a bit like a data constructor, or normal form, of the language.
This contrasts with other approaches that eliminate choice by non-deterministically
picking one branch or the other, which immediately gives up confluence.
