\subsection{The Verse calculus is lenient} \label{sec:lenient}

\versecalc{} is \emph{lenient} \cite{lenience},
not lazy (call-by-need), nor strict (call-by-value).
Under lenient
evaluation, everything is eventually evaluated, but functions can run
before their arguments have a value.
Consider a function
call |apply1 f e|, where |e| is not a value.  In \versecalc{}, applications are in administrative normal form (ANF),
so we must actually write |def x (x==e; apply1 f x)|. This expression will not return a value until
|e| reduces to a value: that is, everything is eventually evaluated.  But even so, |apply1 f x| can proceed
to \textbeta-reduce (\cref{sec:beta}), assuming we know the definition of |f|.

Lenience supports \emph{abstraction}.  For example, we can replace an expression |(x==tup(y,3); y>7)| by
$$
|def f (f == (lam (tup (p,q)) (p==tup(q,3); q>7)); applyN f (x,y)|
$$
Here, we abstract over the free variables of the expression, and define a named function |f|.
Calling the function is just the same as writing the original expression.
This transformation would not be valid under call-by-value.

This is not just a way to get \emph{parallelism}, which was the original motivation for introducing
lenience in the data-flow language Id~\cite{lenience}; it affects
\emph{semantics}. Consider:
$$
|def (f ^^ x ^^ y) (f == (lam p (x==7;p)); y == (if (x>0) then 7 else 8); apply1 f y|
$$
Here, |y| does not get a value until |x| is known; but |x| does not get its
value (in this case |7|) until |f| is called.  Without lenience this program would be stuck.

However, moving to \emph{laziness} seems problematic.
For example, consider: |def x (x == apply0 wombat; 3)|.  In a lazy, language this expression would
yield |3|, but in \versecalc{}, everything is evaluated, and
the expression will not return a value until |apply0 wombat| converges.
There is a good reason for this choice: |apply0 wombat| might fail, and we should not return |3| until
we know there is no failure.  With laziness, we could easily lose confluence.

\subsection{Evaluation strategy} \label{sec:eval-strategy}

Any rewrite rule can apply anywhere in the term, at any time.  For example, in the term |(x==3+4; y==3*2; x+y)|
the rewrite rules do not say whether to rewrite |3+4| $\rightarrow$ |7| and then |3*2| $\rightarrow$ |6|,
or the other way around.
The rules do, however, require us to reduce |3+4| $\rightarrow$ |7| before substituting for |x| in |x+y| because
rule \rulename{subst} only fires when the RHS is a value.
The rewrite rules thereby express \emph{semantics}.

For example, in the lambda calculus, by changing the rewrite
rule \textbeta{} to \textbeta V, we change the language from call-by-name to call-by-value; by
adding {\bf let}, plus suitable rewrite rules, we can express call-by-need \cite{ariola:call-by-need}.
In \versecalc{}, the rewrite rules are carefully crafted in a similar way; for example, \rulename{subst} will
only substitute |x==v| when the equation binds a variable to a \emph{value}, rather like \textbeta V in
lambda calculus.  Similarly, the elimination rules never discard a term that could fail.

In any term there may of course be many redexes---that is good.
An \emph{evaluation strategy} answers the question: given a closed term, which unique redex,
out of the many possible redexes, should be rewritten next to make progress toward the result?
Let us call an evaluation strategy \emph{good} if it guarantees to terminate if there
is \emph{any} terminating sequence of reductions; \ie, if any path terminates with a value,
then a good evaluation strategy will terminate with that same value\footnote{
It would be even better if the strategy could (c) guarantee to find the
result in the minimal number of rewrite steps---so called ``optimal reduction'' \cite{levy1978reductions,lamping1989algorithm,asperti1998optimal}---but optimal reduction is typically very hard, even in theory, and
invariably involves reducing under lambdas, so for practical purposes it is well out of reach.}.
For example, in the pure lambda calculus, \emph{normal-order reduction},
sometimes called \emph{leftmost-outermost reduction}, is a \emph{good} evaluation strategy.

We believe that the same leftmost-outermost strategy is close to being \emph{good} for
\versecalc{}\footnote{
  We say ``close to'' being good because we do not yet have a proof; indeed
  rule \rulename{fail-elim} may be a bit too powerful.
}: just repeatedly reduce the leftmost-outermost
redex, with some tweaks to avoid infinite application of \rulename{exi-swap}.
That is easy in theory, but it is tricky in practice.  For
example, consider |(x+y; tup(x,3)==tup(2,y));x|.  The |(x+y)| is not a
redex, but the equation is; we can apply unification to get |(x==2; y==3)|, and then
substitution to rewrite the |(x+y)| to |(2+3)|; and
\emph{now} the |(2+3)| is a redex.  So a reduction may ``unlock'' a
redex far to its left.  A major challenge of an implementation is to
find the next redex efficiently.

We have several prototype implementations of \versecalc{}, each involving an abstract
machine with a stack, a heap, a bunch of blocked computations, and so on. Exploring this
design space is, however, beyond the scope of this paper.

% The trouble is that it is hard to say what the ``leftmost'' redex is.  For example in |(e; tup(x,3)==tup(2,y))|,
% the equation may or may not be the leftmost redex, depending on whether |e| is stuck ({\ie}, contains no
% redexes); and whether or not |e| is stuck is a not syntactic property, and
