\subsection{Overview of skew confluence} \label{sec:skew-overview-2}

We travel a path very similar to the one blazed by Ariola and her co-authors.
Ariola and Klop studied a form of the lambda calculus with an added $\mathsf{letrec}$ construct and
determined (like us) that their calculus was not confluent; then they added a specific
constraint on recursive substitution
and proved that the modified calculus is confluent \cite{ariola:cyclic-lambda,ariola:lambda-letrec}.
In a later paper, Ariola and Blom proved that their calculus without the constraint, while not confluent,
does obey a weaker related property, which they invented, of \emph{skew confluence} \cite{ariola:skew-confluence}.
We believe, and currently are trying to prove, that \versecalc{} is skew confluent without the
pesky no-recursion side condition of \cref{thm:confluence-sketch}.
\begin{center}
  \begin{tabular}{rl}
    Confluence: & $\forall |e|, |e_1|, |e_2|.\; \rsteps{\rr}{|e|}{|e_1|} \wedge \rsteps{\rr}{|e|}{|e_2|} \implies \exists e'.\; \rsteps{\rr}{|e_1|}{|e'|} \wedge \rsteps{\rr}{|e_2|}{|e'|}$. \\
    Skew confluence: & $\forall |e|, |e_1|, |e_2|.\; \rsteps{\rr}{|e|}{|e_1|} \wedge \rsteps{\rr}{|e|}{|e_2|} \implies \exists e'.\; \rsteps{\rr}{|e_1|}{|e'|} \wedge |e_2| \preceqomegarr |e'|$. \\
  \end{tabular}
\end{center}
These are depicted here as two commutative diagrams, which differ only on the bottom edge:
%
\begin{center}
  \begin{tabular}{c@@{\qquad}c@@{\qquad\quad}c}
  Confluence & Skew confluence & \\
  % https://q.uiver.app/?
\begin{tikzcd}
	e & {e_1} \\
	{e_2} & {e'}
	\arrow["\rr"', two heads, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow["\rr"', two heads, from=1-1, to=2-1]
	\arrow["\rr", dotted, two heads, from=1-2, to=2-2]
	\arrow["\rr"', dotted, two heads, from=2-1, to=2-2]
      \end{tikzcd}
&
% https://q.uiver.app/?
\begin{tikzcd}
	e & {e_1} \\
	{e_2} & {e'}
	\arrow["\rr"', two heads, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow["\rr", dotted, two heads, from=1-2, to=2-2]
	\arrow["\rr"', two heads, from=1-1, to=2-1]
	\arrow["\preceqomegarr", dotted, no head, from=2-2, to=2-1]
\end{tikzcd}
&
\raise0.5ex\hbox{\smash{\fbox{\parbox{18em}{For each diagram, given |e|, |e_1|, |e_2| that obey the relationships
               indicated by all the solid lines, there exists |e'| such that
               all relationships indicated by dotted lines are also satisfied.}}}}
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
%
% \simon{why dotted arrows?}
% The meaning of $|e_2| \inccon{\preceq}{\rr} |e'|$ is that |e_2| is \emph{convertible} to |e'|, but only through a sequence of reductions
% and converse reductions that maintain a certain partial order $\preceqomegarr$ (see below).
% \simon{don't understand this}
You can understand skew confluence as follows: if two different reduction paths from |e| produce
terms |e_1|, |e_2|, then |e_1| can be further reduced to |e'| so that all of |e_2|'s permanent structure
is present in |e'|, written $|e_2| \preceqomegarr |e'|$.  By ``permanent structure'' we mean
an outer shell of tuples, lambdas, and constants, that will never change no matter how much
further reduction takes place.  For example, however far we reduce the term |tup (1, lam z e)|, the
result will always look like |tup (1, lam z e')|, where $\rsteps{\rr}{e}{e'}$.  We can formalize the notion of
permanent structure by defining an
\emph{erasure function} $\omegarr(|e|)$ which replaces all the impermanent bits of |e|
with a new dummy term |Omega|.  Thus $\omegarr(|tup (1, lam z x)|) = |tup (1, lam z Omega)|$.
Then $|e_2| \preceqomegarr |e'|$ if $\omegarr(|e_2|)$ can be made equal to |e'| by
replacing each occurrence of |Omega| in $\omegarr(|e_2|)$ with an (individually-chosen) term.

Consider the even-odd problem discussed in \cref{sec:even-odd}.
$$
\begin{array}{l@@{\,}l@@{\hspace{1cm}}l@@{\,}l}
\multicolumn{4}{c}{|def (x ^^ y) (x == tup (1, y)); y == lam z x; x)|} \\
    \rsteps{}{}{} & |def y (y == lam z (tup (1, y)); tup (1,y))|
  & \rsteps{}{}{} & |def x (x = tup (1, lam z x); x)| \\
    \rstep{}{}{} & |def y (y == lam z (tup (1, y)); tup (1, lam z (tup (1,y))))|
  & \rstep{}{}{} & |def x (x = tup (1, lam z x); tup (1, lam z x)))| \\
    \rstep{}{}{} & |def y (y == lam z (tup (1, y)); tup (1, lam z (tup (1,lam z (tup (1,y))))))|
  & \rstep{}{}{} & |def x (x = tup (1, lam z x); tup (1, lam z (tup (1,lam z x))))| \\
    \rstep{}{}{} & \cdots & \rstep{}{}{} & \cdots
\end{array}
$$
The two columns can never join up, but if you pick any term, there is a term in the other
column that has a greater amount of permanent structure.  That in turn means that the terms in the left-hand
column are contextually equivalent to those in the right-hand column, because the context can
inspect only the permanent structure. This contextual equivalence is the real reason
for seeking confluence in the first place.

In \cref{sec:skew-confluence} we show how to adapt the proof strategy
of \cref{sec:confluence-sketch} and \cref{sec:confluence} for skew confluence.
To do this we need a new result: if two relations are skew confluent
with respect to the same information content function and commute, then their union is also skew confluent.
(In fact, it is not required that the two relations fully commute: a slightly weaker precondition suffices.)
Using this result, our plan
is to (i) define an appropriate information content function for \versecalc{} expressions;
(ii) prove that all the rewrite rules for \versecalc{} are monotonic in this information content function;
(iii) prove that the Unification rules (modified to permit recursive substitution) together with the Normalization rules are skew confluent;
(iv) prove that this combined set of rules commutes in the necessary way with the rules for Application, Elimination, and Choice (which taken together are already known to be confluent);
and (v) then apply our new result to show that the entire set of rewrite rules is skew confluent.
At this time steps (iii) and (iv) are incomplete, so we emphasize that we do not yet have a complete proof of skew confluence for \versecalc{}.


