\subsection{Ordering and choices} \label{sec:ord-choice}

As we discussed in \cref{sec:choice-rules}, rule \rulename{choose} is less than satisfying for two reasons.
First, the |CX| context uses a conservative, syntactic analysis for choice-free expressions; and second,
the |SX| context is needed to force |CX| to be maximal.  A rule like this would be more satisfying:
$$
\rulename{simpler-choose} \quad   |CX^[ e_1 choice e_2 ]| \movesto |CX^[e_1] choice CX^[e_2]|
$$
The trouble with this is that it may change the order of the results (\cref{sec:mixing}).
Another possibility would be to accept that results may come out in the ``wrong'' order, but have
some kind of sorting mechanism to put them back into the ``right'' order.  Something like this:
$$
\rulename{labeled-choose} \quad   |CX^[ e_1 choice e_2 ]| \movesto |CX^[left e_1] choice CX^[right e_2]|
$$
Here, the two branches are labeled with |L| and |R|.  We can add new rules to reorder such
labeled expressions, something in the spirit of:
$$
\rulename{sort} \quad   |(right e_1) choice (left e_2)| \movesto |(left e_2) choice (right e_1)|
$$
We believe this can be made to work, and it would allow more programs to evaluate, but it adds unwelcome clutter to program terms, and the cure may be worse than the disease. However, the idea directly inspired our denotational
semantics (\cref{sec:order-sensitive}), where it seems to work rather beautifully.

\subsection{Generalizing \texorpdfstring{|oneKW|}{``one''} and \texorpdfstring{|allKW|}{``all''}} \label{sec:split}

In \versecalc{}, we introduced |oneKW| and |allKW| as the primitive choice-consuming operators, and neither is more general than the other, as discussed in \cref{sec:all}.
We could have introduced a more general operator |splitKW|\footnote{The name inspired by \citet{oleglogict}.} as $e ::=  |dots| \vb |split e v_1 v_2|$ and rules:
\[\begin{array}{lrcll}
    \rulename{split-fail} & |split fail f g| & \movesto & |apply0 f| \\
    \rulename{split-choice} & |split (v `choice` e) f g| & \movesto & |applyN g (v, thunk e)|  \\
    \rulename{split-value} & |split v f g| & \movesto & |applyN g (v, thunk fail)|  \\
\end{array}\]
The intuition behind |splitKW| is that it distinguishes a failing computation from one that returns at least one value. If |e| fails, it calls |f|, and if |e| returns at least one value, it passes that to |g| together with the remaining computation, safely tucked away behind a lambda.
When adding more effects to \versecalc{}, see \cref{sec:store}, it is in fact crucial to use $|splitKW|$ to exactly control the order of effects.

Indeed, this is more general, as we can implement |oneKW| and |allKW| with |splitKW|:
\[\begin{array}{r@@{\;}l@@{\;}l@@{\;}l}
    |one e| & \equiv |apply1 f x :== fail; | & |applyN g (x,y):== x;| & |split e f g| \\
    |all e| & \equiv |apply1 f x :== emptytup;|    & |applyN g (x,y):== applyN cons (x, split (apply0 y) f g);| & |split e f g|
\end{array}\]
For this paper, we stuck to the arguably simpler |oneKW| and |allKW|,
to avoid confusing the presentation with these higher-order encodings, but there are no complications using |splitKW| instead.

